FIFA 22 continues the tradition of delivering an immersive football experience with its latest installment. From refined gameplay mechanics to enhanced graphics, the game strives to capture the essence of the sport while introducing new features to keep players engaged.

Gameplay:
The gameplay mechanics in FIFA 22 have been tweaked to provide a more realistic and dynamic experience on the pitch. The new HyperMotion technology, exclusive to the next-gen consoles, brings players to life with more fluid movements and smarter decision-making. This adds depth to matches, making each encounter feel unique and unpredictable.

Career Mode:
Career mode receives some welcomed updates, offering players more control over their team's destiny. With improved AI and new features like Create a Club, players can truly shape their footballing journey, whether it's guiding a struggling team to glory or building a powerhouse from scratch.

Ultimate Team:
Ultimate Team remains a cornerstone of the FIFA franchise, and FIFA 22 introduces fresh content and gameplay tweaks to keep the mode exciting. With new player cards, challenges, and events, there's always something to strive for as you build your dream squad.

Volta Football:
Volta Football returns with even more flair and customization options. Whether you're playing in the streets or on a professional indoor pitch, the fast-paced, skill-based gameplay of Volta offers a refreshing alternative to traditional matches.

Graphics and Presentation:
Visually, FIFA 22 impresses with stunning player models, realistic stadiums, and dynamic weather effects that enhance the immersion. The attention to detail is evident throughout the game, from the grass on the pitch to the facial expressions of the players.

Verdict:
FIFA 22 builds upon the solid foundation of its predecessors, delivering an engaging football experience that will satisfy both casual fans and die-hard enthusiasts. With its refined gameplay, expanded modes, and impressive presentation, FIFA 22 continues to be the go-to choice for football gaming enthusiasts. Whether you're a seasoned veteran or a newcomer to the franchise, FIFA 22 offers something for everyone, making it a must-have for any football fan's collection.

FOR THE SALMON FILLING
200g hot smoked salmon (or trout), flaked
¬Ω x 300ml pot half-fat cr√®me fra√Æch
3 tsp horseradish sauce
¬Ω x 20g pack chives, finely chopped
zest and juice of 1 lemon

FOR THE PRAWN FILLING
1 x 250g bag cooked and peeled cold water prawns, defrosted and roughly chopped
100g mayonnaise
100g natural thick Greek yogurt
¬Ω x 20g pack dill, chopped

TO DECORATE
100g fine asparagus, halved lengthways
10 radishes, thinly sliced
1 cucumber, shaved into ribbons (discard the seedy core)

100g smoked salmon

1. First make the fillings; use a fork to combine the salmon, cr√©me fra√Æche, horseradish, chives and lemon zest in a bowl, adding the lemon juice and seasoning to taste. Mix the prawn filling ingredients in another bowl and season. Cover and chill, if prepping ahead.

2. Place a sheet of baking paper over a large cutting board. Lay out 6 slices of crustless bread on the board in two rows of 3 slices,to form a rectangle. Spread the salmon filling evenly over the bread, then top with another 6 slices. Arrange the avocado and sliced eggs on top; season lightly. Add the next layer of bread, followed by the prawn filling, spreading all the way out to the sides. Finish with the last 6 slices of bread, pressing down slightly. Chill for 1 hour to firm up.

3. Beat together the soft cheese, cr√©me fra√Æche and lemon zest until just combined. Spread over the top and sides of the sandwich cake with a palette knife; return to the fridge to set for at least 2 hours (or overnight).

4. To decorate the cake, press raw asparagus and radish slices around the sides. Wrap ribbons of cucumber around the base of the cake. Top the cake with more cucumber ribbons, radish slices and carrot ribbons and the quartered eggs. Make salmon ‚Äòroses‚Äô by wrapping thin strips of smoked salmon around your finger, then dot these around the top. Finally, finish the sandwich cake with small spoonfuls of ‚Äòcaviar‚Äô, if using, and the dill sprigs and/or watercress. Chill until ready to serve.

This game has been notably disappointing, and I will elucidate the array of issues encountered. As a fervent and longstanding enthusiast of the FIFA career mode, several grievances have surfaced. Primarily, the stamina recovery between games is markedly inadequate. Despite configuring the training schedule to intermittent training weekly, with designated rest days and post-match recovery, the recuperation rates remain subpar. Even with players possessing stamina ratings ranging from 72 to 85+, a complete recovery proves elusive, often necessitating a complete overhaul of the starting lineup.

In terms of gameplay, a discernible decline from the previous year is evident. While improvements have been made to crosses and the distribution of long balls between flanks, ball control in possession has regrettably suffered. Players are prone to facile loss of possession, particularly in attacking positions, and through balls are easily intercepted. Despite employing an assertive and attacking tactical approach, reminiscent of previous FIFA iterations, players exhibit a reluctance to engage or respond as anticipated. Defensive maneuvers and coordination lag, rendering it challenging to prevent goals, thus culminating in a palpable sense of frustration.

Personally, the last FIFA that felt like a real game-changer was '15. Since then, it's been a downhill slide into what feels like a money-grabbing mess. Microtransactions have turned it into a cheap pay-to-win circus, and it's frustrating.

The bugs? Don't even get me started. It's like they're part of the FIFA charm now ‚Äì been hanging around for about eight years, like that annoying friend who won't take a hint. Seriously, EA, can we get some bug spray up in here?

My dream fix? How about they drop this yearly release nonsense and give us a game that evolves over seasons? A continuous update instead of this rinse-and-repeat cycle might be the answer. But hey, we're talking about EA Games here ‚Äì not exactly known for groundbreaking ideas.

In a nutshell, FIFA22 feels like a missed opportunity. Instead of moving forward, it's stuck in a loop of mediocrity and a blatant cash grab. Here's hoping one day we get a FIFA that brings back the magic of '15, but until then, it's like watching the same disappointing sequel over and over again. Classic EA move.

Last decent FIFA in a while. FIFA 23 & 24 are both terrible, bug-ridden mess' on PC. FIFA 22 on the other hand at least runs pretty well and I haven't had it crash on me yet in the 70 hours that I've amassed on it. The "New and Improved" career mode is fun, but sadly your custom character maxes out at level 25, making it impossible to unlock all of the skill-trees and become some ungodly rated 99 beast. 

Over all though the game-play feels solid, animations are sometimes very good, other times a bit clunky. Sound design is good enough, and does help with the immersion. Graphics on high are pretty good! There are still some occasional visual bugs, like the hair of blurred players in the background still appearing sharp for some reason? But the lighting, shadows, reflections, and details in the stadiums themselves are really well made. 

The "Volta" mode is fun but gets kinda boring? To be honest I don't know why anyone would buy FIFA for anything but the classic career and kick-off modes... I've never played the FIFA multiplayer modes, and I also didn't in this one, so I can't comment on it, but I am assuming its the same as the past FIFA titles (Online Pro, Packs, etc.) 

So yeah, if you're looking to buy a FIFA game, get this one. Don't get the 23 or 24, they're such disappointments.

Where to begin with FIFA 22? It‚Äôs as if the developers decided to take everything that could have possibly been loved about the FIFA franchise, throw it into a blender, and then pour the mixture into a server that's perpetually on fire. If you're seeking the thrill of football, you're better off knitting socks for your local Sunday league team than enduring this travesty.

The game‚Äôs ‚Äòinnovative‚Äô HyperMotion Technology could have been revolutionary, but instead, it seems to have been designed by someone whose only prior experience with football was a half-remembered PE class from two decades ago. Players on the pitch handle like a supermarket trolley with a busted wheel, veering wildly and rarely going where you want them to.

Ultimate Team? More like the Ultimate Ponzi scheme. The mode is an insidious ploy to pickpocket players under the guise of entertainment, dangling the carrot of elite players in front of us, only to beat us with the stick of reality when we inevitably pull yet another no-name player from a pack.

But let‚Äôs talk about the online experience, shall we? The servers are as reliable as a chocolate teapot. You‚Äôll find yourself disconnected from matches with such frequency that you start to wonder if 'server stability' is just a myth EA Sports made up to tease us. And when you are connected, the lag is so bad it feels like your team is playing in treacle - treacle that's past its sell-by date.

The ball physics are an enigma, defying the very essence of gravity and momentum. The ball floats like a balloon on a breezy day, making every attempt at a pass or shot a game of lottery. And tackling? The referees must be using a rulebook from an alternate universe where contact is a sin because you‚Äôll be penalized for so much as breathing too heavily on an opponent.

Career mode remains a neglected wasteland, where the AI transfers and managerial decisions are about as logical as a cat‚Äôs strategy in a game of chess. And don‚Äôt get me started on the commentary, which has all the variety and excitement of a two-day seminar on watching paint dry.

In essence, FIFA 22 is an overpriced, underperforming shadow of what a football game could and should be. It's a soul-sucking, wallet-emptying husk that masquerades as entertainment. So, if you value your money, time, and love for football, steer clear of this digital doppelg√§nger of despair.

- Player career is broken. Even if you have the match of a lifetime, the amount of XP that gets added compared to what gets taken in between matches is insane, making it nearly impossible to improve and get more playtime
- I play against World Class AI and consistently win with 10+ goals. What I don't understand is why my defense is often so crap. It's like they don't know what they're doing. Could be me, but I often doubt it.

On the other hand, I'm happy with some QOL updates, like being able to skip pre-match cutscenes. Big improvement.

So ehhh careful thumbs up. I hope the games do get better at some point.

As with many others, I played a lot of FIFA when I was a kid ‚Äì FIFA 2000, 2002 World Cup, 2003, 2005 World Cup, 2007, 2008, 2009, and a few pre-2000 titles. Then, I stopped playing. However, recently, I played FIFA 19 with my colleagues at work and realized I wasn't as good as I thought. So, I decided to buy FIFA 22, hoping to improve my skills since I didn't want to keep playing so poorly.

Unfortunately, EA disappointed the PC FIFA player base by not releasing the next-gen version of the game on PC. Instead, they provided the old-gen version, like the one on PS4. The reason behind this decision was that many players have budget PCs, and releasing the next-gen version could split the player base or exclude those with low-end PCs. Just a little background information.

I can only compare FIFA 22 to FIFA 19, as that's the last one I played, but I can say it feels and looks better. Although I'm no expert, it doesn't seem like an entirely new game, more like an updated version. It's surprising how EA manages to release essentially the same game each year, with minor tweaks and feature changes, and market it as a new game, even charging full-game prices. But that's just my opinion.

For me, FIFA 22 was and still is a great way to pass the time, playing a match or two against random people. I mostly lose, but I try my best. xD Despite my lack of success, I have fun playing this way. I did give the career mode a shot, but it didn't captivate me enough to continue. As for the other game modes, I can't really comment since I haven't explored them much. One thing I'm sure of is that people shouldn't go the FUT (FIFA Ultimate Team) road. It feels like a pay-to-win, casino-like simulator, and you end up spending money on a game that loses significance once the next one comes out ‚Äì just my two cents.

Gameplay-wise, FIFA 22 offers a fun experience, depending on what you're looking to get out of it. However, I don't see myself buying any other FIFA anytime soon. One installment is enough for me. If the player base dies out and I can no longer find opponents to play against, so be it. Maybe I'd consider a radically-changed new FIFA game, but I won't pay for just an update.

For achievement hunters: the game has 37 achievements. And I was into completing the game. But unfortunately, at the moment, the Volta (game mode) achievements are broken because the Volta servers are broken themselves. Contacting EA did not help and I am not keeping my fingers crossed either.

To be perfectly candid here: these games have been a fixture in our lives since time immemorial. These games conceived the very sport of football itself, took an extended century-long siesta, and reawakened to the realization that a fresh milking iteration each year equates to a windfall for all it is worth. Think of it as a corporate twist and rendition of the classic monopoly board game‚Äîexcept devoid of top hats.

With each passing year, a promise of revolution echoes through the gaming cosmos. "This time," they proclaim, "we have engineered blades of grass that flex!" Yet, in all sincerity, it is akin to observing my grandfather's hairline‚Äîreceding.

As someone who is the equivalent of a football wizard, this was a breeze. The opponents were like lost sheep, and I was their shepherd, leading my team to victory with all the finesse of a rhinoceros and regarding my prowess on the pitch, it is best likened to how I dribble, I pass, I aim for the goal... or so I endeavor.

As for the graphics, they are nothing short of remarkable. Should I squint my eyes and conveniently disregard the bread crumbs adorning my screen, it approximates the experience of spectating an authentic match. When the in-game athletes appear weary, rest assured they mirror my own fatigue, stemming from the ceaseless button-mashing that assumes life-or-death proportions.

In summation, this franchise may be emblematic of the gaming industry's predilection for repetition, such as heading back to a foray into a fast-food establishment for the umpteenth time. Yet, it remains irresistibly captivating. Until the arrival of the subsequent annual iteration, you shall find me ensconced upon my cherished sofa, with crisps, effervescent libations, and so on.

This game is a true reflection of EA sports. A game with disappointing mechanics and just odd occurrences specifically in online game-play. There is a baffling lack of control on the defensive end. AI players tend to be locked by a invisible gravity that will pull them from making defensive plays. This sequence is more prevalent when an opposing player has a high profile attacker (i.e - Mbappe, Ronaldo, Messi). They will literally run pass the offensive player who has the ball and allow a wide open goal attempt.  That is probably the most uncontrollable and frustrating thing I have seen within a sports game. Its absolutely ridiculous that in 2022 release from a franchise this issues like this exist. Also freshly subbed players getting outpaced on the outside.I can't even think about buying a future game , because of the lack of features and poor mechanics within the game. If you want your game to be big and profitable as possible, deliver to the people buying the products in a way that creates an enjoyable but fair gaming experience. This means give people control and allow skill to let the best player win. The internet tug of war is terrible. I have 1,000 mbps internet and have laggy games, which is the testament to how bad my experience is. This player force field nonsense will keep me from looking at another title especially for full price. This game cannot be recommended if you actually want your play to be the defining factor of an outcome. I wanted to revise my original review which is extremely critical in hindsight. After even more play I have come to appreciate the game more. Its bright spots are definitely the game's physics. There is this inexplicable magic which is the shooting. They managed to make it feel stunningly close to real life. Successfully timed releases are polished and smooth to the touch. Offense is extremely joyful , more so with players with supreme skill. While in the past I had my gripes with the defense I have to give credit in the areas that are good. The challenges and tackles are crisp and work well when timed. Also you can feel the synergy of players and formations that is super intuitive. Overall I would recommend this game because the positives outweigh the negatives. This game is super addictive quick entertainment that allows you to be creative on the pitch .

As an avid soccer enthusiast, I recently had the opportunity to dive into the virtual world of FIFA 22, and I must say, it exceeded my expectations in every aspect. This latest instalment of the popular FIFA franchise, developed by EA Sports, has truly raised the bar for soccer video games, delivering an immersive and exhilarating gaming experience. Here's why I highly recommend FIFA 22 to all my fellow gamer and soccer fanatics:

Unparalleled Realism: FIFA 22 takes realism to a whole new level. From the incredibly detailed player models to the lifelike animations, every aspect of the game feels remarkably authentic. The improved player AI ensures that matches are filled with strategic plays and intelligent decision-making, making each game a true representation of the beautiful game we all love.

Next-Gen Graphics: With the power of next-generation consoles, FIFA 22 showcases stunning visuals that bring the stadiums, players, and environments to life. Whether you're playing in iconic stadiums like Camp Nou or experiencing the thrill of international tournaments, the level of detail is astonishing. The graphics create an immersive atmosphere that adds to the overall excitement of the game.

Enhanced Gameplay Mechanics: FIFA 22 introduces several gameplay improvements that make each match feel more dynamic and engaging. The new HyperMotion technology, exclusive to the next-gen consoles, adds a layer of fluidity to player movements, making the gameplay smoother and more responsive than ever before. The revamped ball physics and player interactions add depth to the gameplay, creating intense and realistic on-field battles.

Extensive Game Modes: FIFA 22 offers a wide range of game modes that cater to different preferences. Whether you enjoy the competitive nature of online play or prefer a more relaxed experience with friends, there's something for everyone. From the classic Career Mode, where you can manage your favorite team to glory, to the popular Ultimate Team, which lets you build and customize your dream squad, FIFA 22 keeps you engaged with its diverse gameplay options.

Authentic Licenses and Immersive Audio: FIFA 22 boasts an impressive collection of officially licensed teams, leagues, and players, giving you access to the most authentic soccer experience available in a video game. The crowd chants, stadium ambience, and commentary all contribute to the immersive audio experience, making you feel like you're right in the heart of the action.

In conclusion, FIFA 22 has truly set a new standard for soccer video games. With its unparalleled realism, next-gen graphics, enhanced gameplay mechanics, extensive game modes, and authentic licenses, this game is a must-have for both soccer enthusiasts and gaming aficionados alike. I highly recommend FIFA 22 to all my friends, as it promises countless hours of immersive soccer action and unrivaled excitement. Get ready to step onto the virtual pitch and experience the thrill of soccer like never before!

I am a 50 year old father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my son, who is now 14. My son recently started Fifa 22 and in less than a week, he had already played for over 20 hours. This was terrible for me, as it was already hard enough for me to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching videos on Tiktok. So i decided to make a Steam account and download this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, looked at the menu, but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought my son and I closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

Finally FIFA 22 became free on mobile. Around $80 on steam store and consoles to play with controller. Apple app store is making it free now to make iPhone users believe why do you pay for a smartphone with world-class brand. It depends on individual expertise to handle touch screen buttons or controller to have a real test of the gaming.

BEGINNER-INTERMEDIATE-EXPERT, three levels of training to play personally in this game. At the beginner level SHOOTING-PASSING-DRIBBLING-DEFENDING trainings are mandatory to unlock player training options to train individual payers in your team. Use of touch screen on iphone is subtle but realistic in sense when I was mastering the angles of shooting, drbbling and such. Must be trained to use both thumbs in proper harmony. Seems like you must earn money to train each and every player of your ultimate team to upgrade their skills. There is daily logging reward. Choose my name, team logo and few things for the ‚Äúultimate team‚Äù that was given to me also can be setup by pressing the setting button on the top of the screen. 

Setting button also let you set up graphics of the game and other. Must download things like English commentator for the games. On the top left of your screen you'll see your personal status as a player with your game center name. If I click on MY TEAM I get options to SUBSTITUTE-LINEUP-PIECES-FORMATION which is a ongoing process to develope the team that you'll see how ‚Äúskill move‚Äù & ‚Äúskill boost‚Äù systems work. 21 player tab on the screen allow you to select 11 players for the match. 

Got some reward packs during my training sessions to leave the beginning level to intermediate then lined up my team with players given to me in a kick off pack. Now setting individual pieces like team captain and player selection for executing corner kicks, free kicks and penalty kicks. On the screen clicked each player‚Äôs name in my team to know their skills then put them in positions. Easy job looking at various world rankings as well. Anyways there are auto-build and default option to auto select these things. Now I can see there is price tag for the value of my team. Also can see bunch of skills a player can have to use them in right position in right time of the game. FORMATION of the player in the field must be handy like 4-3-3 or such to have players in position during the match when playing. 3 basic Formations ATTACKING MODE-BALANCE MODE-DEFENCIVE MODE.

Before you press the kickoff button to start a match you must be prepared and learned with all above personal training and player training & positioning options in this game. Now hope for the best if you can continue to up skill your players and your personal techniques to use the touch screen in the real environment of game play in a match. Some buttons on the bottom of your screen will be gradually unlocked when you personally improve your levels to participate in this game. 

At the intermediate level, played two ‚ÄúSKILL GAMES‚Äù to learned ‚Äú1 ON 1 SOOTING‚Äù and having a teammate to pass and support the goal to finally dodge the goalkeeper to goal in the match. 

4 buttons on the left thumb SPRINT-KICK-PASS-THROUGH which will change a bit when ball is in the hand of opposition. 1 button on right thumb to use it as joystick to control the directions of the player. Reached level 3 after the personal training. Then played the real match to win and get to expert level. Things are unlocking at the bottom of the screen now. Few more skill matches to learn PENALTY SHOOTING-TEAMMATE CROSSING to become expert to get on with the job. Finished first two matches at normal difficulty level to become expert. All buttons on the screen are now unlocked to enjoy the game.

FIFA 22 is the latest installment in the popular football simulation video game series developed by EA Sports and released in 2021. The game features updated graphics, new features, and improved gameplay mechanics.

One of the game's main strengths is its realistic representation of football gameplay. The game offers a vast selection of teams and players from around the world, each with their unique play styles and abilities. The graphics in the game are impressive, with realistic player models and detailed environments that capture the atmosphere of a football match. Additionally, the game features a variety of new modes, including the Career Mode, which allows players to manage a team and compete in various leagues and tournaments.

The gameplay mechanics in FIFA 22 have been refined, with improved ball control and player movement. The game also offers a new feature called HyperMotion, which uses motion capture technology to create more realistic and dynamic player movements.

However, the game can feel repetitive at times, with matches sometimes feeling too similar to each other. Additionally, some players may find the game's microtransactions and loot boxes to be frustrating, as they can be a barrier to fully enjoying the game without spending additional money.

Overall, FIFA 22 is a highly realistic and engaging football simulation game that offers a variety of new features and gameplay improvements. While the game's repetitive gameplay and microtransactions may not appeal to everyone, those who enjoy football and are looking for a realistic and immersive experience will likely find this game to be a worthwhile addition to their collection.

FIFA 22 is yet another disappointing release from EA Sports. As someone who has played every FIFA game, I can confidently say that this is the worst one yet. From the moment I started playing, I could feel the frustration building inside of me. The controls are clunky and unresponsive, making it nearly impossible to execute even the simplest of moves.

But it's not just the controls that are terrible - the entire gameplay experience is a mess. The AI is completely braindead, and the graphics are somehow worse than they were in FIFA 21. It's as if EA Sports didn't even bother trying to improve anything from the previous game.

And let's not even get started on the Ultimate Team mode. It's a complete cash grab, designed to suck as much money out of players as possible. The loot box system is predatory and the matchmaking is rigged, making it nearly impossible to compete without spending real money.

Honestly, I hate every FIFA game and EA Sports as a company. They've turned what used to be a fun and enjoyable pastime into a soul-sucking, money-grabbing nightmare. I wouldn't recommend FIFA 22 to my worst enemy. Save your money and find something else to play - anything else would be better than this garbage.

Sooooo... You think you play good football and that is the only thing you need to win in this game? Naaaa bruh...
So let me just explain to you how things work:

You start a match with your overall 80-85 score team right all golden regular cards you own the shit out of your noob opponent that payed 500e to buy complete team of football legends from the 60'70'80' and ofc they all have overall score of 99 with max boosts and stuff idk...

So you are shooting left and right BUT this game will allow you to maybe score one goal in the first half so you shoot 15 shoots you get 1 goal 10 crossbars and 4 situations where your player would str8 up trip on his own foot or something when he is in a 100% scoring situation.

So you continue playing the other half, it's the same situation until minute 80 then the scripting takes over and NO MATTER WHAT YOU DO you cannot win. The game will do EVERYTHING in it's power to create a situation where you cannot defend against the most basic action in the universe. In the end when you loose the match it's unbelievably annoying I'm not gonna lie, it's fking rage inducing. This game saved my life.

I am 27.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and adopted our son together. They are now both 4 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I found myself lost and miserable. I was self destructive. I got so mad one day from everything spiraling out of my control that I punched some concrete in a moment of overwhelming emotion. That caused me to break my 5th metacarpal in my right hand... my working hand... my games hand.. the hand that I held and carried my children to bed with.. The hand I desperately needed to make sure I could continue to provide.

After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô• minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

After coming to that realization, I turned the game off, and I went back to work. It hurt my hand like hell but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so damn sorry for myself, and I became the father I needed to be in that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving as.

Today, I am close friend with my kids mother. We don't fight, or argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents, and friends.

I now have 3 kids. My third child is, wait for it, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my own separation, and we just stumbled in to each others life unexpectedly. We have been in a relationship for a year now, and are very happy together.

Moral of the story, you never know what life holds in store for you, and if I would have given up when all the odds were stacked against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

Thank you

For shots inside the box, their response can be unrealistically catlike or infuriatingly malcoordinated. For shots outside the box, it doesn't look like they're even trying. If you can buy FIFA 22 on sale, buy it. It is still better than the cesspit that is FIFA 23 - there's always a reason why a game still has mixed reviews 3/4 the way through its lifespan.

I been playing Fifa since 1998 except 2018 to 2021 and I have to say this 22 version has some bold pros and some terrible cons.
Cons: 
1- Launching the game is a nightmare. I'm not bad with computers but hate the extra struggle specially when I am short on time. However since EA app came out it has been improved but still some struggle. If Origin was still out then I surely would have not recommended this game.
2- In career mode the transfer market as it has always been is way off from what happens in real world. You could sell a bunch of junk players easily and buy a star with the money and the star usually accepts the move if the money is right. too easy to make an all star team in 2-3 seasons.
3- That bug with arrows in the menu is so so annoying for a 2022 title! sometimes you cannot browse your messages or select a player from the squad hub and you have to restart the game. Some other weird bugs happen during goal celebrations from time to time which is minor.
4- The gap between legendary and world class difficulties is huge. It maybe because of the competitor mode which is enabled for legendary and ultimate difficulties. In those difficulties even an average player plays like a legendary star so defending becomes a nightmare and for dribbling a well timed skill move is required.
5- As always been with fifa no matter How I change the tactics forwards wont come back to defend and 1st and 2nd player chasing the ball is almost useless. the player only chases the ball like a blind person and have no awareness of the attacker body and what he will do next. Maybe that's why everyone says defending is impossible in Fifa 22.
6- Goal keepers are awful! They sometimes do miracles but usually concede with ease,
7- some career mode goals are buggy or not well explained.
Pros:
1- Killer sound tracks as always is with EA titles
2- I have been playing football myself and the physique of the game is so realistic that the outcome of a missed time run or shot does not surprise me. You have to consider the real life mechanics and the game responds well which is amazing. That's the main reason I recommend this game.
3- vast range of difficulty keeps you entertained enough
4- Player development in career mode is well designed.
5- Transfers, player search and doing business is fun albeit not accurate.

As a long-time fan of the FIFA franchise, I have to say that FIFA 22 is an excellent addition to the series. With updated graphics, smoother gameplay, and more realistic animations, the game immerses you in the world of football like never before.

The Career Mode has also received some much-needed improvements, with more detailed player and manager interactions and improved AI. I found myself getting more invested in my team's progress than ever before, as every decision I made felt like it had real consequences.

There are still some minor issues, such as occasional bugs and glitches, but they are few and far between and do not detract from the overall experience.

Overall, FIFA 22 is a fantastic game that any football fan should pick up. With its improved gameplay, updated graphics, and new features, it is the most complete football experience on the market. I highly recommend it.

I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well.

As someone who has recently played FIFA 22, I can say that it is a fantastic soccer simulation game. The game offers a high degree of realism and depth, with a vast array of teams, players, and leagues to choose from.

One of the things I appreciated most about the game was the level of control it gave me on the field. The controls are smooth and responsive, making it a joy to play. The AI of the game is also well-done, with opposition teams and players behaving realistically based on their attributes and the tactics you employ.

Another aspect of the game that I appreciated was the level of customization available. From the various tactics and formations available, to the option to create custom teams and players, the game offers a high degree of player choice and replayability.

The graphics and presentation of the game are top-notch, providing a visually appealing experience. The commentary and sound design are similarly well-done, further adding to the game's immersive quality.

Overall, I highly recommend FIFA 22 to anyone who loves soccer or is looking for a simulation game that offers a high degree of realism and depth. Whether you're a fan of the franchise or new to the series, this game is sure to provide hours of enjoyable gameplay.

I know it sounds strange with the amount of hours I have in the game but hear me out. I only the career mode so if your here FUT, keep scrolling. The game feels a bit messy, sometimes the game doesn't respond to my inputs, resulting in my attacks coming to a standstill. The menus get stuck and only fixed by using the mouse (not deal breaker but annoying when it happens every session). Sometimes I can steam roll big teams (like Chelsea or United, even in later years in the career with a mid table team), but struggle against teams at the bottom, or even lower leagues, it makes no real sense and is a problem in fifa for years now. Also the loan system still isn't 100%, like players who would get a load of game time still won't join your team and you will be rejected 90% of the time. Overall since it's on EA play and does go dirt cheap at times, you should give it a go and lets all hope the next EA football game (whatever they called it, can't remember and I don't really care) is a good one.

The first few matches meant a lot of unusual for me. I tried to thread the ball through a gap in the opponent's midfield, a foreign defender stretched out his leg and blocked the ball. "I could have gotten away with this last year!" I assured myself confusedly.
Unlike in years past, games don't tend to see double-digit goals scored because defenses manage to not be completely incompetent. It's true that the stoppers could be a little more wallpapered on the attackers, because sometimes it happens to me that a foreign forward ends up completely unoccupied in the goal, but at least the defensive midfielders, who last time... Well, who just didn't exist last time, are drawn into the defense.
It's great that even a missed kick, just like in real football, can turn into a chance like a frog into a handsome prince. A desperate ball forward doesn't mean an automatic loss if you have Lewandovski, Mbappe or some such diabolical hybrid racing in front of you.

The new FIFA looks fantastic on next-gen, which is to be expected. But I didn't expect it to play so well. On the pitch, it's still not a pure simulation like PES, but everything is more tactical and fun, including card-based Ultimate Team. That career alone deserves to be significantly polished.
And it would definitely help to add a story campaign, like last year had a short but very invigorating story in the form of VOLTA football. [b] 65% [/b]

I am a 43 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just, watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. loaded into the game, made my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you were supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he helped me. Loved it as it was the best time had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

I never normally do game reviews but I have to for this.  I‚Äôm a big fan of fifa, played a lot of it over the years but this game is such a let down. The graphics are decent especially on the new console, however, the gameplay is awful. I‚Äôve only played FUT so far, and although not being like a Messi superstar playing it I tend to be quite decent most of the time, but this gameplay is just shocking. Firstly, the fact that the goal keepers are ridiculously overpowered, or, if it‚Äôs your own keeper, shockingly awful. They never catch a ball, they throw their hands up and let it bounce away, normally letting the opposite team get a goal. Or if you strike a ball, no matter how close, it goes right to their hands, no curve whatsoever even with a finesse shot. The defending is awful, defenders don‚Äôt mark any players and just swarm to one player leaving the whole defence open. Player ratings seem to mean nothing these days, you‚Äôre better off having a whole team of 82 rated players and saving your in game money because even the higher rated strikers can‚Äôt put a ball in the net half the time. Also THE THROUGH BALLS ARE THE WORST. You‚Äôll be doing your opponent a favour by playing a through ball, normally goes to anyone other than your own players And if your player gets tackled, he spends about 15 minutes falling/getting back up, ruining any chance of attacking once you‚Äôve broken through. My opinion, Fifa 21 is far better than fifa 22, I‚Äôm going to keep playing obviously, it‚Äôs as addictive as meth, but Jesus, overall a very poor game in my opinion.

I am a 43 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just, watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. loaded into the game, made my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you were supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he helped me. Loved it as it was the best time had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

My first FIFA game since 2017.
I hated Ultimate Team. Main reason: Most players play with the exact same team, just slight chances and play the exact same way. They only care about winning. It became so boring so quickly.

But my main mode always was Career Mode:

Player Career Mode feels very odd. I made a shit CDM, chose Tottenham and was a starting player instantly.
Then i went on to score every single long-shot I took.
It's just bad.

Team Career Mode: playing the AI is just boring and often times unplayable. After 1 season 1 quit, then I downloaded a gameplay mod and then the game became a decent amount of fun.
The tasks from the board are most of the times retarded non-sense.

In my first save, I created a team in the 3rd Bundesliga. Only goal was to 'fight against relegation'. Most of the season I was bottom 2 but then I became a bit better at the game and made it up to 16th place with 7 or 8 games to go. 
And then I got fired. Even achieved the other tasks - I think there was only 1 which was to sell 2 players or sth.

In my 2nd save, I took over a 4th division english team. Multiple times I found 85+ rated free agents at the start of the season that were very happy to join me - while I was in the 2nd/3rd division - and were happy to accept 500 quid a week.
Idk about that.
In general, so many important aspects were absolutely non-sense.

Scripted horseshit. One match your players will play normally, the next they move like bags of sand with dumbbells tied around their ankles. Once the AI decides you're going to lose a game, you'll lose it regardless of what you do. All of your passes will suddenly mishit their target, shots go wide, you lose every header, 1-on-1 and 2nd ball while your opponent plays like prime Barcelona on steroids, effortlessly juggling their way past your hapless, often completely passive defenders who stand around staring stupidly like glorified training cones.

0/10.

My name is Walter Hartwell White. I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104. This is my confession. If you're watching this tape, I'm probably dead, murdered by my brother-in-law Hank Schrader. Hank has been building a meth empire for over a year now and using me as his chemist. Shortly after my 50th birthday, Hank came to me with a rather, shocking proposition. He asked that I use my chemistry knowledge to cook methamphetamine, which he would then sell using his connections in the drug world. Connections that he made through his career with the DEA. I was... astounded, I... I always thought that Hank was a very moral man and I was... thrown, confused, but I was also particularly vulnerable at the time, something he knew and took advantage of. I was reeling from a cancer diagnosis that was poised to bankrupt my family. Hank took me on a ride along, and showed me just how much money even a small meth operation could make. And I was weak. I didn't want my family to go into financial ruin so I agreed. Every day, I think back at that moment with regret. I quickly realized that I was in way over my head, and Hank had a partner, a man named Gustavo Fring, a businessman. Hank essentially sold me into servitude to this man, and when I tried to quit, Fring threatened my family. I didn't know where to turn.
Eventually, Hank and Fring had a falling out. From what I can gather, Hank was always pushing for a greater share of the business, to which Fring flatly refused to give him, and things escalated. Fring was able to arrange, uh I guess I guess you call it a "hit" on my brother-in-law, and failed, but Hank was seriously injured, and I wound up paying his medical bills which amounted to a little over $177,000. Upon recovery, Hank was bent on revenge, working with a man named Hector Salamanca, he plotted to kill Fring, and did so. In fact, the bomb that he used was built by me, and he gave me no option in it. I have often contemplated suicide, but I'm a coward. I wanted to go to the police, but I was frightened. Hank had risen in the ranks to become the head of the Albuquerque DEA, and about that time, to keep me in line, he took my children from me. For 3 months he kept them. My wife, who up until that point, had no idea of my criminal activities, was horrified to learn what I had done, why Hank had taken our children. We were scared. I was in Hell, I hated myself for what I had brought upon my family. Recently, I tried once again to quit, to end this nightmare, and in response, he gave me this. I can't take this anymore. I live in fear every day that Hank will kill me, or worse, hurt my family. I... All I could think to do was to make this video in hope that the world will finally see this man, for what he really is.

Got this game for two main reasons: ultimate team and career manager mode.

First game in UT rivals, I've got my starter pack and, despite rivals mode being described as "matching players of similar skill", my very first opponent had all legendary players with 90+ skill. Either matchmaking's broken as hell, or there's no player base for the game.

Manager mode was way more complex than it used to be, which is fantastic as people always complain about the games being too similar. After returning from a 5 year absence, I was happy to see a lot more depth to your options. Then I got terminated by the board mid-season, despite my confidence rating being in 80's. Turns out the wages are just broken and if you renew a contract and give a player a bit more money, that's basically an instant termination.

I'd refund the damn thing, but it takes about 2 hours just to get through the EA login bullshit, so you're kinda boned from the get go.

Sure you can build a decent side by putting a couple of hundred hours in, but why would you when every year your every effort is rendered a waste of time?

I would be on board if I could move my hard won ultimate team from version to version... but as it stands I'm done with this scam.  Pay to win is such a curse on modern gaming, and it creates a two tier experience I reject utterly.

I am a 54-year old father, probably one of the oldest people playing Apex Legends. 
I am a single father to my son, who is now 14. My son recently started playing Apex Legends. 
In less than a week, he had already played for over 20 hours. 
This was terrible for me because it was already hard enough for me to spend time with my son 
because he was always out with his friends or watching YouTube. So I decided to make a Steam 
account to play with my son. I started playing, but this was my first time playing a video game
 since the 90's, so I was quite lost. I asked my son for help, and together we spent some hours playing Apex Legends. 
I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my son since my wife had died. Playing video games 
reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought 
me and my son closer again, and now we actually spend time together outside the house as well.

FIFA 22 has no story mode. But it has done some improvements in gameplay compared to its predecessors. Graphics are also good on pitch. PES lost its career mode and FIFA's became better. However lots of good things FIFA didn't do or ruined in this edition.
1.  Pathetic unchangeable background colors according to league played in career definitely hurts eyes. 
2. Controls are good but PES was smoother and less complicated to take free kick and penalty. 
3. Lots of Licenses but some important ones missing like Serie A teams like Juventus.
4. Career menus especially player reports look very bad and outdated,
5. All created players have 4 star. No chance to alter skills to 5 star for created players.
6. As usual kits names etc can't be changed so you can't edit real Serie A teams like PES. Juve remains Piemonte with fake kits.

Played Fifa 2022 and 2023 and honestly I can't tell the difference.  

In 2023 what you notice as a different is a different menu system and a bit more colour saturation on certain parts of the game, its essentially the same game.  

I have been playing 2022 more than 2023 lately.   Given that I've only have 2023 on trial (EA Play) vs own 2022 and lately, playing 22 has really gotten better.  I don't know where to put my finger on it, but play on the field seems to me at least improved.  I've noticed handling the ball is more responsive, and positioning of AI players is there.  2022 feels more immersive from when I played a few months ago to now.  The Hypermotion tech in 2023 to me, I can't tell where it is compared to 2022.  Animations are great from full stops, turns and overall movement.  Maybe I just need more time with 2023 to see the difference, but I just don't see it...  

If you last played Fifa 2022 a few months or even a few weeks ago, give 2022 a go and you won't regret it. especially when this goes on sale. It's a no brainner to get this over 2023 right now.  You would be basically be paying $89 (CND) for the same game in another skin... This is way better than Esport 2023 right now that's for sure.  Also, you don't have to worry about the anti-cheat non-sense in 2023...

Save your money and keep 2022 if you already have it, its not worth the upgrade.  If its on sale and you're looking for some football action. just pick it up.

Yes, I've logged a lot of hours. Will I keep playing the game? Yes. Would I recommend it to anyone? No, unless you haven't purchased a Fifa game in like 5 years. 

I purchased this game mainly for the updated roster, including because a player that I follow (who has the same last name as me) has his (my) last name announced in games. Made this a lot more fun to do my career mode. Otherwise, the career mode is fairly boring--no story, too much variability on teams (rosters do full overhauls yearly, even if they win everything), and the commentary in-game is recycled garbage. You basically hear the same 4-5 things after every goal, even if they were very different goals. Just give us a good story with stuff to do, similar to the NBA games, otherwise the career thing feels like a joke! 

From what I've seen (I played a bit on friends' consoles) and they've nerfed the PC title, but still want to charge us 60-70 dollars for the game!! I bought it on sale elsewhere ($15) and I don't feel like I got $15 dollars worth of game. I don't know the next time I will buy another Fifa title if it stays like this, this one was a must buy due to the name thing so I don't have any regrets there.

If you own Fifa 18-21, there's nothing new here in terms of gameplay, graphics, etc...if you want it just for the roster upgrade, please wait until there's a sale. Need to show EA Sports we won't put up with this crap, especially for PC.  

tldr; Not worth full price. Get only if you haven't purchased in several years, otherwise skip!
